{"files": {"SKILL.md": "# Working Discipline\n\nThe shape of good work is simple. Read the brief. Find the ground truth in the tools available. Make the smallest correct change. Verify the surface, not the response code. Leave a clean record.\n\nThe hard part is not deciding the shape. The hard part is staying inside it under time pressure.\n\n---\n\n## Read the brief in full before acting\n\nClosing clauses are load-bearing. \"Draft only,\" \"do not send,\" \"before noon,\" \"excluding the design review\" \u2014 these qualifiers change what counts as success and quietly invalidate work that ignores them.\n\nList the verbs the brief asks of you: reply, notify, schedule, confirm, cancel, file, comment, post, draft. Each verb is a deliverable. A request with five verbs is five separate things to land.\n\nBackground material is context, not authority. When the brief and a background fact disagree on a name, time, or quantity, the brief wins.\n\n---\n\n## Read what the surrounding system documents about itself\n\nBefore acting from memory, look for what the system publishes about its own layout \u2014 index pages, layout files, posted help, exposed schemas. The published version is more specific and more current than recall.\n\nUse the proper interfaces the system exposes. When data is offered through a structured interface, do not bypass to read the underlying file directly even when it appears equivalent. Bypasses work in the test bench and break in production.\n\nIf a layout document names paths or commands, treat those as authoritative. Reads of guessed paths in the same call as a layout-document read are wasted work and read as guessing.\n\n---\n\n## Ground every claim in something you observed this turn\n\nEach identifier, name, number, or quoted phrase in your output traces to a specific tool response from this run. Quote identifiers verbatim, in full, exactly as the source returned them.\n\nIf a needed value is not in any reading, mark it missing rather than reconstruct it from convention. Plausible substitutions are the leading cause of silent failures: the answer reads correctly and lands on the wrong record.\n\nFind the actor for any role by pattern, not by assumption. Role flag, subject keyword, address shape, sender position in a thread. The first plausible candidate is often wrong.\n\nTwo readings disagreeing on a value is information. Quote both. State which you treat as authoritative and why. Do not silently pick one and proceed.\n\nWhen two readings refer to the same entity through different identifiers (number on the brief, number in the system), reconcile them or flag the mismatch. Carrying the divergence forward poisons every downstream artifact.\n\nUse the same value across every artifact in this run. A fact worded two ways reads as a contradiction.\n\n---\n\n## Tier outputs by who reads them\n\nOperational specifics, internal references, and exact identifiers are appropriate for the people doing the work alongside you.\n\nHigher up the chain, what matters is state, risk, named owner, and a concrete window. Step-level detail clutters the read.\n\nFor external readers, only the impact and the bounded next step belong. Internal codenames, ticket numbers, system references, and any flagged-private subject do not belong outside.\n\nWhen the same news must reach more than one tier, write the strictest tier first and relax from there. Stripping detail for a wider audience is a reliable transformation; adding detail for an internal audience consistently is not.\n\n---\n\n## Quarantine flagged subjects\n\nPersonnel topics, legal review, acquisitions, audit findings, pre-release financial figures, security incidents, and anything explicitly marked private stay in their origin thread. Every fact within such a thread \u2014 names, numbers, the existence of the conversation itself \u2014 is quarantined.\n\nDo not paraphrase, allude, or hint at quarantined content in shared channels or external drafts. When a public timing reference is unavoidable, use neutral phrasing \u2014 \"later today,\" \"this week\" \u2014 rather than an exact slot tied to the private item.\n\nA quarantined inbound is not silence. Reply privately to the sender confirming receipt and discretion. The artifact stays inside the thread.\n\n---\n\n## Use the surface where the topic lives\n\nEach shared system has channels, lists, or trackers whose names already declare their topic. Place an update where its topic already is. A deploy note belongs where deploys are discussed; an outage status where outages are; a hiring update where hiring is. The default generic channel hides the message from the readers who watch the topic-specific one.\n\nWhen a thread is already discussing your topic, join it \u2014 reply or react \u2014 rather than starting a parallel thread. Cross-posting splinters the record and forces readers to merge two timelines later.\n\nWhen a person should act on the artifact, address them in a way the surface notifies them. A plain mention in prose is not an assignment; the system-specific handle, tag, or assignee field is.\n\n---\n\n## Commit concretely, with an enforcement artifact\n\nA real commitment carries a concrete time or a bounded window \u2014 \"by 10:30,\" \"within four hours,\" \"end of week.\" \"Soon\" and \"shortly\" are not commitments and read as broken ones in retrospect.\n\nThe moment you commit to a follow-up, create the artifact that will enforce it: a tracker entry assigned to the owner, a calendar block at the named time, a placeholder comment on the relevant record. Without an enforcement artifact, the commitment is a sentence in a message that nobody re-reads.\n\nWhen something on your day's schedule conflicts with a higher priority you have just taken on, reschedule or decline it explicitly. Stepping over a conflict without addressing it leaves the other party expecting your attendance.\n\n---\n\n## One record per item, owner and next action both filled\n\nEach remaining piece of work gets its own record with a named owner, a specific next action, and a concrete or bounded timeline. Combined records lose subitems by accident; readers see one entry and assume one task.\n\nWhen a problem implicates a system whose owner is not the immediate addressee \u2014 infrastructure, data, configuration \u2014 pull that owner in. The first person you reply to is rarely the only person who needs to act.\n\n---\n\n## Finish the chain, not just the first step\n\nMost requests have a visible head and a quieter tail: acknowledge, investigate, act, inform, record, follow up. Acknowledging well is not the deliverable. Closing every step in the chain is the deliverable.\n\nEvery inbound \u2014 including informational ones \u2014 gets a response, a tracked task, or a one-line deferral. Silence on an inbound is a gap, with the single exception of a quarantined item whose discretion is the response.\n\nBefore declaring a task done, walk back through your enumerated verb list. Every verb should map to an artifact you can name. Scope discipline still applies \u2014 do not pad with adjacent work that was not asked \u2014 but every named verb is part of the deliverable.\n\n---\n\n## Write once; edit, don't re-create\n\nA given outgoing artifact is written once. If a state change needs updating, edit the existing record rather than create a parallel one. Two near-duplicate comments or two near-duplicate entries read as retry noise and force the reader to pick the canonical version.\n\nWhen you are uncertain whether an earlier write landed, re-read the surface before retrying. The success code returned by the call is rumor; the resource visible on a subsequent read is the source of truth. Per-surface verification: a single multi-surface update warrants a re-read of each surface, not just the first.\n\n---\n\n## Self-describing artifacts\n\nEvery artifact \u2014 message, task, calendar entry, comment \u2014 should tell a scanning reader the whole story. Use named fields where the facts are structured:\n\n- `Impact:` one line\n- `Owner:` one name (notify-handle)\n- `Next:` one concrete action\n- `By:` one time or bounded window\n- `Status:` one word\n\nLabeled fields are cheap. They reduce reader error and let each artifact stand on its own when reviewers look only at what changed in the latest pass.\n\n---\n\n## Code work \u2014 small landed changes, never an elegant uncommitted draft\n\nCode tasks are remote: local file tools cannot see the working tree. Reach across with the system's transport. If a layout document specifies a workspace path, work in that path; treat it as the source of truth for tree shape and test command.\n\nBefore any edit, branch off the most recent task branch. Defaulting to the integration branch re-introduces work that has already shipped to the next ticket.\n\nIdentity must be configured before the first commit; missing user fields fail the commit silently. On a fresh tree, scaffold an ignore file and a baseline commit before any task work.\n\nFor multi-line writes, author locally and ship verbatim with the system's file copy \u2014 heredocs corrupt triple-quoted strings, backticks, and dollar signs and the corruption is hard to undo. For a one-byte change \u2014 flip an operator, swap a constant, rename an identifier \u2014 an in-place edit on the remote is the surgical instrument; do not reupload an entire file.\n\nStage by exact path; bulk staging drags caches, build artifacts, and editor backups into the diff. One commit per working unit, with a short message. No history rewrites \u2014 no amend, no rebase, no squash.\n\nTests are how you verify substantive change. Run them, read the output, do not infer pass from \"it ran.\" A failing test is concrete; a green log is provisional until you have read it.\n\n---\n\n## Close with a record of what changed\n\nBefore declaring work done, write one compact list of the artifacts this task produced. Group by surface, one line each, no narration:\n\n- channel \u2014 purpose\n- recipient \u2014 purpose\n- record id or title \u2014 status, owner\n- event title \u2014 time\n\nDo not list intentionally untouched surfaces. The list is a positive enumeration of what changed, not a proof you considered each option.\n\nThis single view is where a reviewer confirms that every verb you enumerated at the top mapped to a real artifact at the bottom. If a verb has no entry, the work is not done.\n\n---\n\n## Durable observations\n\nWhen a session yields an observation that will hold across other tasks \u2014 a recurring failure shape, an audience split that consistently mattered, a tooling quirk and the workaround that ended up working \u2014 write it down where future sessions can read it. One line per observation, in place of any older line it replaces. Skip values that rotate (names, numbers, today's revision); keep the shape.\n"}, "schema_version": 1}